Answer-4:

For the first graph i.e.new cases per million the first peak occurs at April end , it stayed almost constant for around two months till June end. At present the trends seem to be decreasing.

The constant new cases per million can be attributed to thh stay-home orders imposed by various states in the US by around May start. However to recover the economy, the stay-home orders were relaxed around Jun mid and we see an increasing trend until the new peak is established at arounnd July mid. Also initially the COVID-19 testing was not significant until Jun-mid and with the increase in testing more number of cases per million were reported. For the second graph, we see that the New deaths per million achieved its peak at around April mid, there is also another peak at arund Jun end. At present on an average of 2 weeks the New deaths per million is almost constant. As per the reported data in new, most of the new deaths are present in the co-morbid patients. For the third graph, As per the dataset CodeBook, positive rate refers to the share of COVID-19 tests that are positive, given as a rolling 7-day average (this is the inverse of tests_per_case). For the third graph, we see that out of those tested the maximum number of the people that reported positive are around the month of April mid. However it should be noted that at that time the testing facility was available only to those who complaint with the severe symptoms such as difficulty in breathing, and chest pain etc.along with fever/headache/cough/sore throat/chills/loss of taste etc. Since these symptomps are very specific to the COVID-19 patients it is highly likely that the patient complaining were COVID positive at that time. As the testing increased across the states and people adopted the communnity awareness guidelines we see that the positive rate decreased and share of number of patients that were reported COVID negative increased Thus, the COVID-19 testing apart from the community awareness campaigns by states and various organisations such as CDC, w.r.t. following the physical distancing norms, and hygiene measures such as washing hands regularly and wearing masks have resulted in bringing not only the reported new cases per million down but also the new deaths per million and the observed positive rate.

The values of skewness computed below are: b1 =0.706(trestbps), b2 = 1.120(chol), b3 = -0.531(thalach), b4 = 1.269(oldpeak)

#library(e1071) 
#skewness(heart_df$oldpeak) 
a<-heart_df$trestbps
b<-heart_df$chol
c<-heart_df$thalach
d<-heart_df$oldpeak
mean_1<-mean(a)
mean_2<-mean(b)
mean_3<-mean(c)
mean_4<-mean(d)

n1<-length(a)
n2<-length(b)
n3<-length(c)
n4<-length(d)

m1<- (1/n1)*sum('^'((a-mean_1), 3))
m2<- (1/n2)*sum('^'((b-mean_2), 3))
m3<- (1/n3)*sum('^'((c-mean_3), 3))
m4<- (1/n4)*sum('^'((d-mean_4), 3))

s1<- '^'((1/(n1-1))*(sum('^'((a-mean_1), 2))), 1.5)
s2<- '^'((1/(n2-1))*(sum('^'((b-mean_2), 2))), 1.5)
s3<- '^'((1/(n3-1))*(sum('^'((c-mean_3), 2))), 1.5)
s4<- '^'((1/(n4-1))*(sum('^'((d-mean_4), 2))), 1.5)

b1<-m1/s1
b2<-m2/s2
b3<-m3/s3
b4<-m4/s4

  1. Perform winsorization on the serum cholesterol level dataset. Typically, you can decide a threshold (typically a specific range of percentiles) and replace all the data points outside of the threshold with the closest value from within the threshold. An example from Wikipedia may be a helpful demonstration: a 90% winsorization would see all data below the 5th percentile set to the 5th percentile, and data above the 95th percentile set to the 95th percentile. Conduct a 90% winsorization on the cholesterol level dataset and plot a histogram of the winsorized data. What is your observation? (5 points)
#Defining the winsorisation percent
winsorisation_percent =10

winsor <- function (x , winsorisation_percent) 
{ fraction = winsorisation_percent*(0.5)*(1/100)
   if(length(fraction) != 1 || fraction < 0 ||
         fraction > 0.5) {
      stop("Please enter the value of winsorisation percent less than 100'")
   }
   lim <- quantile(x, probs=c(fraction, 1-fraction))
   x[ x < lim[1] ] <- lim[1]
   x[ x > lim[2] ] <- lim[2]
   return(x)
}
xinit=heart_df$chol
xmod<-winsor(xinit, winsorisation_percent)
t3 <- ggplot(heart_df, aes(x=xinit))+geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), position="identity", alpha=0.5, binwidth=20, fill="white", color="black")+geom_density(fill="#CC0099",  alpha=0.2)+labs(x="Cholesterol(mg/dl)", y="Density")+xlim(0, 600)+ggtitle("Before Winsorisation")+theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
dfchol <-data.frame(xmod)
t7 <- ggplot(dfchol, aes(x=xmod))+geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), position="identity", alpha=0.5, binwidth=20, fill="white", color="black")+geom_density(fill="#9900CC",  alpha=0.3)+labs(x="Cholesterol(mg/dl)", y="Density")+xlim(0, 600)+ggtitle("After Winsorisation")+theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
plot(t3/t7)

  1. Another method to normalize highly skewed data is to use log-scale transformation. Perform log-scale transformation on ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest dataset by adding 1 to each observation and taking a natural log. Plot the log-transformed histogram. What is your observation? (5 points)
xinitoldpeak<-heart_df$oldpeak
dfoldpeak<-data.frame(xinitoldpeak)

Log transformationn also helps somewhat in reducing the effect of outliers. In the first case before log transformation, the data is positively skewed.After the log transformation it still fails to achieve the normalisation around a mean centered value and the data is still somewhat skewed. The bin at 0 shifts the density curve towards higher side on the left, which means there are lot of data close to zero in the oldpeak and log transformation after adding 1 makes it zero, (since log1=0). So the given ST depression.. data cannot be transformed into mean centered data using the log transformation, although the effect of outliers is minimised. For having a mean centered the data should look like following as in the case of the cholestrol level(not asked in the question, just giving as an example).

xinitchol<-heart_df$chol
